PostHistory.xml:842:  <row Id="900" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="358" RevisionGUID="548ff7ab-ad63-4428-a5d8-68e10ee36ec8" CreationDate="2010-09-22T22:24:57.577" UserId="567" Comment="added a paragraph about the fact that the question has been closed" Text="Currently the question “[Do you use any article organizers?](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1574/do-you-use-any-article-organizers)” has three votes to close as off topic.  However, in my opinion, this question can be interesting to people working on theoretical computer science and is not off topic, although it is not a question _in_ TCS.  At least I am interested in what other people in TCS use.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;(As I wrote in a [post to another discussion](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/333/protocol-for-accepting-answers-in-cw-and-list-type-questions/337#337), I am a little bit tired of big-list questions, and this question may be one of them, but that is a separate story.)&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Also, if you are a theoretical computer scientist looking for good citation organization software, I can imagine a reason for you to want to ask for recommendations of other theoretical computer scientists rather than researchers in other fields; it can be expected that they have similar requirements to you.  In this sense, I can argue that the question is _about_ TCS, although admittedly the relation is not strong.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Is this question on topic or off topic?&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;_Added:_ The question has been closed as off topic.  If that is the consensus of people here, I am fine with that, even though it was a little surprising to me because I had an impression that most people were [happier with non-technical or broad questions than with technical, focused questions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions?sort=votes).  Honestly speaking, I personally prefer technical, focused questions than highly-voted soft or broad questions.&#xD;&#xA;" />
PostHistory.xml:843:  <row Id="901" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="358" RevisionGUID="1040029e-c48e-4e17-803a-dbcacf192a91" CreationDate="2010-09-22T22:30:08.613" UserId="567" Comment="added a paragraph about the fact that the question has been closed" Text="Currently the question “[Do you use any article organizers?](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1574/do-you-use-any-article-organizers)” has three votes to close as off topic.  However, in my opinion, this question can be interesting to people working on theoretical computer science and is not off topic, although it is not a question _in_ TCS.  At least I am interested in what other people in TCS use.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;(As I wrote in a [post to another discussion](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/333/protocol-for-accepting-answers-in-cw-and-list-type-questions/337#337), I am a little bit tired of big-list questions, and this question may be one of them, but that is a separate story.)&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Also, if you are a theoretical computer scientist looking for good citation organization software, I can imagine a reason for you to want to ask for recommendations of other theoretical computer scientists rather than researchers in other fields; it can be expected that they have similar requirements to you.  In this sense, I can argue that the question is _about_ TCS, although admittedly the relation is not strong.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Is this question on topic or off topic?&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;_Added:_ The question has been closed as off topic.  If that is the consensus of people here, I am fine with that, even though it was a little surprising to me because I had an impression that most people were [happier with non-technical or broad questions than with technical, focused questions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions?sort=votes).  Honestly speaking, I personally prefer technical, focused questions than highly-voted soft or broad questions, so I guess that I should feel happy to see that this question has been closed as off topic rather than feeling sad.&#xD;&#xA;" />
PostHistory.xml:856:  <row Id="914" PostHistoryTypeId="2" PostId="368" RevisionGUID="a07acf71-e816-4674-aa9a-bf86f1524ea0" CreationDate="2010-09-23T08:26:42.253" UserId="270" Text="Lance Fortnow asked a question, [What is the Volume of Information?](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1593/what-is-the-volume-of-information), which Ross Snider criticised on two grounds:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;1. Off topic: *I downvoted because I don't find this question relevant to the site (despite how infinitely interesting it is). It really doesn't meet the qualifications in the FAQ so far as I can tell*, and&#xD;&#xA;2. Not advanced as a TCS question: *the question (while legitimate and interesting) isn't really a TCS question (and so is not appropriate), and also doesn't meet the qualification here ([meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/225/…](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/225/official-faq-for-theoretical-computer-science/235#235))*&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'm generally of the opinion that the physical basis of computation is fundamental to computer science &amp;mdash;slogan: computer science is ultimately a physical science, one that involves a lot of formal science&amp;mdash; and is perfectly amenable to formal treatment.  Indeed, quantum computation could hardly be treated rigorously if that were not so.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'm guessing that Ross' objection is not on those grounds, but rather he finds Lance's question to be the kind of question that has too much physics in it to be good for this site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Are we worried about this?  Should we resist questions whose TCS to physics quotient gets too low?&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;*Related: [Scope of questions?](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/17/scope-of-questions)*&#xD;&#xA;" />
PostHistory.xml:859:  <row Id="917" PostHistoryTypeId="2" PostId="369" RevisionGUID="bce67e2c-f0c8-4dca-8788-f6be96e34d68" CreationDate="2010-09-23T08:45:27.750" UserId="270" Text="It should be clear that I think physics has an important overlap with theoretical computer science.  The real concern is that these kinds of question provoke the worst kind of answers.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Let me denounce what we might call **cargo-cult physics**, where a perfectly competent TCS researcher might read such a question, think, &quot;oh, I read something about that in Baez's *This week's finds!*&quot; and races off to Wikipedia, quickly skims a few articles to digest some technical terms, and throws together an as authoritative sounding an answer as can be cobbled together from such partly understood material.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;We should try to insist that answers here will stand up to criticism from professional physicists.  Maybe we should help get [the physics proposal][1] rolling, which might be able to help us later: it has some professional physicists committed.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://area51.stackexchange.com/proposals/1908/physics" />
PostHistory.xml:862:  <row Id="920" PostHistoryTypeId="2" PostId="372" RevisionGUID="0db42bd6-37c9-44ca-8e4a-f9fe2809a2e6" CreationDate="2010-09-23T14:35:00.453" UserId="15" Text="Honestly, I'm amazed that this question can be viewed as off-topic. It seems to me that cstheory is the perfect place to ask about whether some concept has an existing crisp formulation.  Previous questions in this vein have included asking about &lt;a href=&quot;http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/668/is-there-a-complexity-theory-analogue-of-rices-theorem-in-computability-theory&quot;&gt;something in the spirit of Rice's theorem in complexity theory&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/399/analogs-of-compressed-sensing&quot;&gt;my own question on analogs for compressed sensing&lt;/a&gt;.  Information theory is most definitely a part of theoretical computer science, and asking about whether the concept of volume, borrowed from physics, can be suitably formalized or not in an information theoretic sense is undeniably a valid one.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Moreover, while I'm all for being more strict about soft questions, I feel that being pedantic about the scope of technical questions is going to be a big turn-off to some people.  cstheory is not supposed to be an elite club or something.  It's the virtual equivalent to a coffee break in a conference.  And Fortnow's question would certainly make for interesting conversation there.  Also, the more types of questions we allow, the more people we bring in from different backgrounds, which only helps the cause of growing this site." />
PostHistory.xml:871:  <row Id="929" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="225" RevisionGUID="050fe5d9-5ad7-4d3e-b9a0-1c1e7f614536" CreationDate="2010-09-24T01:11:14.913" UserId="567" Comment="added : How do I delete my own question/answer?" Text="This is the official site FAQ for Theoretical Computer Science. This question will contain a list of questions, with each question linking to a **single** answer. If there is prior discussion on an answer, or you wish to discuss a particular answer, please create a separate meta question and link to it (so that this FAQ remains uncluttered). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;The scope of this site:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; - [Are questions about *[this area of computer science]* on-topic here?](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/225/official-faq-for-theoretical-computer-science/234#234)&#xD;&#xA; - [What kind of questions are too easy?](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/225/official-faq-for-theoretical-computer-science/235#235)&#xD;&#xA; - [Specific questions about Theorem X in paper Y?](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/225/official-faq-for-theoretical-computer-science/238#238)&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;How to use this site:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; - [Can I discuss questions and answers on cstheory.sx?](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/225/official-faq-for-theoretical-computer-science/232#232)&#xD;&#xA; - [I can't see any formulas!](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/225/official-faq-for-theoretical-computer-science/237#237)&#xD;&#xA; - [What is a *[Math Processing Error]*?](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/225/official-faq-for-theoretical-computer-science/237#237)&#xD;&#xA; - [How do I write formulas?](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/225/official-faq-for-theoretical-computer-science/237#237)&#xD;&#xA; - [How do I copy-and-paste a formula?](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/225/official-faq-for-theoretical-computer-science/233#233)&#xD;&#xA