PostHistory.xml:1294:  <row Id="1383" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="d5e0d6c6-4213-48cb-8ca6-6e0b79c37760" CreationDate="2010-10-28T17:46:03.263" UserId="123" Comment="small edits to &quot;who the site is targeted at&quot;" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Some background####&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Who is the site targeted at###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;The theory Q&amp;A site is aimed at researchers working in theoretical computer science and related fields.  However, anyone who has questions (or answers to questions) relevant to the theory community is  welcome to post, regardless of the poster's reputation within or outside the website.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Things you can do with the site ###&#xD;&#xA;Here, we want specific success stories:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; - open problems being resolved&#xD;&#xA; - researchers connecting in a way that would be difficult otherwise (the Kintali/Stolee example)&#xD;&#xA; - simple questions revealing open problems&#xD;&#xA; - motivation for new students coming into theory&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Reputation, and how the mechanics work###&#xD;&#xA;in short: 'don't worry too much about reputation'&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1295:  <row Id="1384" PostHistoryTypeId="2" PostId="584" RevisionGUID="f49caf20-63eb-4950-bc65-f0a36b91fe0c" CreationDate="2010-10-28T18:25:50.797" UserId="77" Text="My inclination is to say definitely not. Although I can see the benefit – I have 2 open positions – I can imagine that very quickly the amount of noise (for non-job hunters) will increase. There are several thousand computer science departments in the world and each of them probably has between 2 and 20 open positions. This could result thousands of advertisements. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps more to the point is that there is no discussion associated with a job advertisement, and this site is about discussion." />
PostHistory.xml:1296:  <row Id="1385" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="9c3dd228-7cf0-43f4-b252-b1dd596667a2" CreationDate="2010-10-28T18:42:29.507" UserId="77" Comment="added 646 characters in body" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Wikipaedia defined _crowdsourcing_ as &quot;the act of outsourcing tasks to a large group of people or community (a crowd), through an open call.&quot; Imagine doing so with the research questions that trouble you day to day. Or perhaps applying crowdsourcing to help gain understanding in some intricate detail of the latest $P\neq NP$ proof. Or perhaps to assess the viability of a certain proof technique. Or to obtain the latest references in quantum information theory. cstheory.stackexchange.com enables this kind of interaction by bringing together both experts and new researchers from across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Some background####&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Who is the site targeted at###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;The theory Q&amp;A site is aimed at researchers working in theoretical computer science and related fields.  However, anyone who has questions (or answers to questions) relevant to the theory community is  welcome to post, regardless of the poster's reputation within or outside the website.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Things you can do with the site ###&#xD;&#xA;Here, we want specific success stories:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; - open problems being resolved&#xD;&#xA; - researchers connecting in a way that would be difficult otherwise (the Kintali/Stolee example)&#xD;&#xA; - simple questions revealing open problems&#xD;&#xA; - motivation for new students coming into theory&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Reputation, and how the mechanics work###&#xD;&#xA;in short: 'don't worry too much about reputation'&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1297:  <row Id="1386" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="7d39e9bd-8a3a-456e-b027-0bc9ef630c55" CreationDate="2010-10-28T19:22:39.923" UserId="186" Comment="motivation for new students" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Wikipaedia defined _crowdsourcing_ as &quot;the act of outsourcing tasks to a large group of people or community (a crowd), through an open call.&quot; Imagine doing so with the research questions that trouble you day to day. Or perhaps applying crowdsourcing to help gain understanding in some intricate detail of the latest $P\neq NP$ proof. Or perhaps to assess the viability of a certain proof technique. Or to obtain the latest references in quantum information theory. cstheory.stackexchange.com enables this kind of interaction by bringing together both experts and new researchers from across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Some background####&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Who is the site targeted at###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;The theory Q&amp;A site is aimed at researchers working in theoretical computer science and related fields.  However, anyone who has questions (or answers to questions) relevant to the theory community is  welcome to post, regardless of the poster's reputation within or outside the website.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Things you can do with the site ###&#xD;&#xA;Here, we want specific success stories:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; - open problems being resolved&#xD;&#xA; - researchers connecting in a way that would be difficult otherwise (the Kintali/Stolee example)&#xD;&#xA; - simple questions revealing open problems&#xD;&#xA; - motivation for new (graduate) students coming into theory&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;The site is also useful for graduate students. Often new graduate students do not know which area they want to work in as they are not familiar with various areas. By reading questions and answers posted by more senior people they can quickly gain breadth and develop a feeling toward what is going on in various areas and what they want to work on. Many answers cite references and can lead to interesting problems to work on. Students can also post questions they face while reading papers. Answers from experts are more than just answers, they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks (e.g. [Russell's answer](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453)). They will also feel as a part of our community. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Reputation, and how the mechanics work###&#xD;&#xA;in short: 'don't worry too much about reputation'&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1299:  <row Id="1388" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="a6fd74eb-4259-4a95-a6bb-3cf417f33450" CreationDate="2010-10-28T21:12:16.033" UserId="123" Comment="lots of edits, mostly stylistic, to the &quot;some background&quot; section" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Some background####&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Wikipaedia defines _crowdsourcing_ as &quot;the act of outsourcing tasks to a large group of people or community (a crowd), through an open call.&quot; Imagine crowdsourcing helping with problems that come up in research, illuminating some intricate details of a new and difficult proof, assessing the viability of a certain proof technique, or gathering the latest references in quantum information theory. cstheory.stackexchange.com enables this kind of interaction by bringing together researchers from across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Who is the site targeted at###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;The theory Q&amp;A site is aimed at researchers working in theoretical computer science and related fields.  However, anyone who has questions (or answers to questions) relevant to the theory community is  welcome to post, regardless of the poster's reputation within or outside the website.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Things you can do with the site ###&#xD;&#xA;Here, we want specific success stories:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; - open problems being resolved&#xD;&#xA; - researchers connecting in a way that would be difficult otherwise (the Kintali/Stolee example)&#xD;&#xA; - simple questions revealing open problems&#xD;&#xA; - motivation for new (graduate) students coming into theory&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;The site is also useful for graduate students. Often new graduate students do not know which area they want to work in as they are not familiar with various areas. By reading questions and answers posted by more senior people they can quickly gain breadth and develop a feeling toward what is going on in various areas and what they want to work on. Many answers cite references and can lead to interesting problems to work on. Students can also post questions they face while reading papers. Answers from experts are more than just answers, they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks (e.g. [Russell's answer](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453)). They will also feel as a part of our community. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Reputation, and how the mechanics work###&#xD;&#xA;in short: 'don't worry too much about reputation'&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1300:  <row Id="1389" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="a11beaba-9f46-4480-97b0-05ba99dbc19f" CreationDate="2010-10-28T21:32:58.557" UserId="123" Comment="small edits" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Some background####&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Wikipaedia defines _crowdsourcing_ as &quot;the act of outsourcing tasks to a large group of people or community (a crowd), through an open call.&quot; Imagine crowdsourcing helping with problems that come up in research, illuminating some intricate details of a new and difficult proof, assessing the viability of a certain proof technique, or gathering the latest references in quantum information theory. cstheory.stackexchange.com enables this kind of interaction by bringing together researchers from across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Who is the site targeted at###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;The theory Q&amp;A site is aimed at researchers working in theoretical computer science and related fields.  However, anyone who has questions (or answers to questions) relevant to the theory community is  welcome to post, regardless of the poster's reputation within or outside the website.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Things you can do with the site ###&#xD;&#xA;Here, we want specific success stories:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; - open problems being resolved&#xD;&#xA; - researchers connecting in a way that would be difficult otherwise (the Kintali/Stolee example)&#xD;&#xA; - simple questions revealing open problems&#xD;&#xA; - motivation for new (graduate) students coming into theory&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;The site is also useful for graduate students. Often new graduate students do not know which area they want to work in as they are not familiar with various areas. By reading questions and answers posted by more senior people they can quickly gain breadth and develop a feeling toward what is going on in various areas and what they want to work on. Many answers cite references and can lead to interesting problems to work on. Students can also post questions they face while reading papers. Answers from experts are more than just answers, they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks (e.g. [Russell's answer](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453)). They will also feel as a part of our community. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Reputation, and how the mechanics work###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Both questions and answers on the site are voted up or down by users and sorted by their score.  Upvotes are cast for questions and answers that are clear and informative.  Eventually, the best and most interesting content makes its way to the top of the site.  Questioners also have the opportunity to accept a response as the official answer to their question.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;As extra incentive to produce good content, users get reputation points for having highly upvoted posts, having accepted answers, and so on.  The mechanics of this aren't important, but high reputation gives users certain privileges like voting to &quot;close&quot; inappropriate questions.  This helps make the site a real community, moderated by its most constructive users.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1308:  <row Id="1397" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="5e83c342-3ac1-45f7-b721-8d743aebe86d" CreationDate="2010-10-29T12:39:03.287" UserId="77" Comment="Expanded text about stack exchange and how it works" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Some background####&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Wikipaedia defines _crowdsourcing_ as &quot;the act of outsourcing tasks to a large group of people or community (a crowd), through an open call.&quot; Imagine crowdsourcing helping with problems that come up in research, illuminating some intricate details of a new and difficult proof, assessing the viability of a certain proof technique, or gathering the latest references in quantum information theory. cstheory.stackexchange.com enables this kind of interaction by bringing together researchers from across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Who is the site targeted at###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;The theory Q&amp;A site is aimed at researchers working in theoretical computer science and related fields.  However, anyone who has questions (or answers to questions) relevant to the theory community is  welcome to post, regardless of the poster's reputation within or outside the website.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Things you can do with the site ###&#xD;&#xA;Here, we want specific success stories:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; - open problems being resolved&#xD;&#xA; - researchers connecting in a way that would be difficult otherwise (the Kintali/Stolee example)&#xD;&#xA; - simple questions revealing open problems&#xD;&#xA; - motivation for new (graduate) students coming into theory&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;The site is also useful for graduate students. Often new graduate students do not know which area they want to work in as they are not familiar with various areas. By reading questions and answers posted by more senior people they can quickly gain breadth and develop a feeling toward what is going on in various areas and what they want to work on. Many answers cite references and can lead to interesting problems to work on. Students can also post questions they face while reading papers. Answers from experts are more than just answers, they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks (e.g. [Russell's answer](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453)). They will also feel as a part of our community. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###StackExchange and its mechanics###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;cstheory.stackexchange.com is based on the StackExchange family of websites, each devoted &#xD;&#xA;to questions and answers about a specialised topic area. Other well-known&#xD;&#xA;StackExchange sites include StackOverflow.com, devoted to programming, and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org, devoted to research-level mathematics. More generally the topics covers by different sites in the StackExchange family include statistical analysis, home improvement, GIS, tex/latex, personal finance and money, &#xD;&#xA;English language and usage, user interfaces, unix and linux, cooking, and many more.&#xD;&#xA; &#xD;&#xA;The StackExchange software provides various mechanisms and incentives to ensure that &#xD;&#xA;users are encouraged to produce high quality content such as good questions and &#xD;&#xA;well-thought out responses. These mechanisms also work to reduce the amount of spam&#xD;&#xA;and other undesirable content on the site, and  to keep the &#xD;&#xA;questions asked on topic.  These mechanisms include up- or down-voting &#xD;&#xA;questions and answers, flagging spam and other inappropriate content, and receiving _badges_ as rewards for good questions and answers or sustained activity.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Both questions and answers on the site are voted up or down by users and sorted by their score. Upvotes are cast for questions and answers that are clear and informative. Eventually, the best and most interesting content makes its way to the top of the site. Questioners also have the opportunity to accept a response as the official answer to their question.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;As extra incentive to produce good content, users get reputation points for having highly upvoted posts, having accepted answers, and so on. The mechanics of this aren't important, but high reputation gives users certain privileges like voting to &quot;close&quot; inappropriate questions. This helps make the site a real community, moderated by its most constructive users, ensuring the smooth-running of the site and maintaining a high quality of questions and answers.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;StackExchange websites differ from more traditional wiki-sites in that they use a question/answer &#xD;&#xA;instead of community-editable pages of content. &#xD;&#xA;Some questions and answers may be marked as &quot;community wiki&quot;, which enables &#xD;&#xA;them to be edited by all users. These questions can take the form of a big &#xD;&#xA;list collecting together information about a particular topic,&#xD;&#xA;where the community actively gathers together to provide a coherent resource as an answer&#xD;&#xA;to a particular request [EXAMPLE]. Rather than providing a debate on a particular issue, users&#xD;&#xA;can edit existing answers to enhance them with new information and provide a coherent&#xD;&#xA;answer to the question.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1311:  <row Id="1400" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="296609c7-f3ee-464b-b94e-64a13e7d706b" CreationDate="2010-10-30T10:49:09.843" UserId="1677" Comment="Added another possible kind of success story. I don't know if there have been any of these yet, though" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Some background####&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA