various areas and what they want to work on. Many answers cite references and can lead to interesting problems to work on. Students can also post questions they face while reading papers. Answers from experts are more than just answers, they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks (e.g. [Russell's answer](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453)). They will also feel as a part of our community. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###StackExchange and its mechanics###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;cstheory.stackexchange.com is based on the StackExchange family of websites, each devoted &#xD;&#xA;to questions and answers about a specialised topic area. Other well-known&#xD;&#xA;StackExchange sites include StackOverflow.com, devoted to programming, and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org, devoted to research-level mathematics. More generally the topics covers by different sites in the StackExchange family include statistical analysis, home improvement, GIS, tex/latex, personal finance and money, &#xD;&#xA;English language and usage, user interfaces, unix and linux, cooking, and many more.&#xD;&#xA; &#xD;&#xA;The StackExchange software provides various mechanisms and incentives to ensure that &#xD;&#xA;users are encouraged to produce high quality content such as good questions and &#xD;&#xA;well-thought out responses. These mechanisms also work to reduce the amount of spam&#xD;&#xA;and other undesirable content on the site, and  to keep the &#xD;&#xA;questions asked on topic.  These mechanisms include up- or down-voting &#xD;&#xA;questions and answers, flagging spam and other inappropriate content, and receiving _badges_ as rewards for good questions and answers or sustained activity.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Both questions and answers on the site are voted up or down by users and sorted by their score. Upvotes are cast for questions and answers that are clear and informative. Eventually, the best and most interesting content makes its way to the top of the site. Questioners also have the opportunity to accept a response as the official answer to their question.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;As extra incentive to produce good content, users get reputation points for having highly upvoted posts, having accepted answers, and so on. The mechanics of this aren't important, but high reputation gives users certain privileges like voting to &quot;close&quot; inappropriate questions. This helps make the site a real community, moderated by its most constructive users, ensuring the smooth-running of the site and maintaining a high quality of questions and answers.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;StackExchange websites differ from more traditional wiki-sites in that they use a question/answer &#xD;&#xA;instead of community-editable pages of content. &#xD;&#xA;Some questions and answers may be marked as &quot;community wiki&quot;, which enables &#xD;&#xA;them to be edited by all users. These questions can take the form of a big &#xD;&#xA;list collecting together information about a particular topic,&#xD;&#xA;where the community actively gathers together to provide a coherent resource as an answer&#xD;&#xA;to a particular request [EXAMPLE]. Rather than providing a debate on a particular issue, users&#xD;&#xA;can edit existing answers to enhance them with new information and provide a coherent&#xD;&#xA;answer to the question.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1312:  <row Id="1401" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="d2efb57f-aa11-4631-b912-22184a6a98bc" CreationDate="2010-10-30T18:29:24.727" UserId="30" Comment="deleted 36 characters in body" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit cstheory.stackexchange.com###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;cstheory.stackexchange.com provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;The site is also useful for graduate students. Often new graduate students do not know which area they want to work in as they are not familiar with various areas. By reading questions and answers posted by more senior people they can quickly gain breadth and develop a feeling toward what is going on in various areas and what they want to work on. Many answers cite references and can lead to interesting problems to work on. Students can also post questions they face while reading papers. Answers from experts are more than just answers, they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks (e.g. [Russell's answer](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453)). They will also feel as a part of our community. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###StackExchange and its mechanics###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;cstheory.stackexchange.com is based on the StackExchange family of websites, each devoted &#xD;&#xA;to questions and answers about a specialised topic area. Other well-known&#xD;&#xA;StackExchange sites include StackOverflow.com, devoted to programming, and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org, devoted to research-level mathematics. More generally the topics covers by different sites in the StackExchange family include statistical analysis, home improvement, GIS, tex/latex, personal finance and money, &#xD;&#xA;English language and usage, user interfaces, unix and linux, cooking, and many more.&#xD;&#xA; &#xD;&#xA;The StackExchange software provides various mechanisms and incentives to ensure that &#xD;&#xA;users are encouraged to produce high quality content such as good questions and &#xD;&#xA;well-thought out responses. These mechanisms also work to reduce the amount of spam&#xD;&#xA;and other undesirable content on the site, and  to keep the &#xD;&#xA;questions asked on topic.  These mechanisms include up- or down-voting &#xD;&#xA;questions and answers, flagging spam and other inappropriate content, and receiving _badges_ as rewards for good questions and answers or sustained activity.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Both questions and answers on the site are voted up or down by users and sorted by their score. Upvotes are cast for questions and answers that are clear and informative. Eventually, the best and most interesting content makes its way to the top of the site. Questioners also have the opportunity to accept a response as the official answer to their question.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;As extra incentive to produce good content, users get reputation points for having highly upvoted posts, having accepted answers, and so on. The mechanics of this aren't important, but high reputation gives users certain privileges like voting to &quot;close&quot; inappropriate questions. This helps make the site a real community, moderated by its most constructive users, ensuring the smooth-running of the site and maintaining a high quality of questions and answers.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;StackExchange websites differ from more traditional wiki-sites in that they use a question/answer &#xD;&#xA;instead of community-editable pages of content. &#xD;&#xA;Some questions and answers may be marked as &quot;community wiki&quot;, which enables &#xD;&#xA;them to be edited by all users. These questions can take the form of a big &#xD;&#xA;list collecting together information about a particular topic,&#xD;&#xA;where the community actively gathers together to provide a coherent resource as an answer&#xD;&#xA;to a particular request [EXAMPLE]. Rather than providing a debate on a particular issue, users&#xD;&#xA;can edit existing answers to enhance them with new information and provide a coherent&#xD;&#xA;answer to the question.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1320:  <row Id="1409" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="e67164b4-fcd3-4ee2-92c9-246a471416fd" CreationDate="2010-10-31T14:48:19.070" UserId="30" Comment="added 191 characters in body" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/)###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;While some questions, and answers, are highly technical, the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, people have asked for more general advice from the community, on everything from [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic) to &quot;[how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).&quot;  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account and post questions and answers.  Almost all active users are posting under their real names, and we encourage everyone who joins to follow suit.  There is no financial obligation to participate.  _Please note: Homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting &#xD;&#xA;questions and answers, to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.  As one example, this announcement you are reading right now was written by a group of users on cstheory-Meta.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) had participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to crowdsource questions to an international audience of experts.  We felt that emulating the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow was the logical thing to try, and we're very pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1331:  <row Id="1420" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="657a039a-2fa5-4474-b727-bbbf9e781bcb" CreationDate="2010-11-01T08:00:14.733" UserId="80" Comment="added 136 characters in body" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Current contributors (please update)**: Dave Clarke, Kaveh (?), Lev Reyzin, Peter Shor, Aaron Sterling, Suresh Venkatasubramanian.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/)###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;While some questions, and answers, are highly technical, the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, people have asked for more general advice from the community, on everything from [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic) to &quot;[how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).&quot;  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account and post questions and answers.  Almost all active users are posting under their real names, and we encourage everyone who joins to follow suit.  There is no financial obligation to participate.  _Please note: Homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting &#xD;&#xA;questions and answers, to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.  As one example, this announcement you are reading right now was written by a group of users on cstheory-Meta.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) had participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to crowdsource questions to an international audience of experts.  We felt that emulating the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow was the logical thing to try, and we're very pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1332:  <row Id="1421" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="58516cd3-989a-4846-bdad-dc14a4428acc" CreationDate="2010-11-01T09:14:16.727" UserId="186" Comment="added 6 characters in body" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Current contributors (please update)**: Dave Clarke, Kaveh Ghasemloo, Lev Reyzin, Peter Shor, Aaron Sterling, Suresh Venkatasubramanian.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/)###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;While some questions, and answers, are highly technical, the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, people have asked for more general advice from the community, on everything from [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic) to &quot;[how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).&quot;  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account and post questions and answers.  Almost all active users are posting under their real names, and we encourage everyone who joins to follow suit.  There is no financial obligation to participate.  _Please note: Homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting &#xD;&#xA;questions and answers, to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.  As one example, this announcement you are reading right now was written by a group of users on cstheory-Meta.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) had participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to crowdsource questions to an international audience of experts.  We felt that emulating the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow was the logical thing to try, and we're very pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1335:  <row Id="1424" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="c905b67a-b315-41c8-a31e-fe252c377bbd" CreationDate="2010-11-01T17:59:28.207" UserId="109" Comment="some copy editing and a few new sentences" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Current contributors (please update)**: Dave Clarke, Kaveh Ghasemloo, Lev Reyzin, Peter Shor, Aaron Sterling, Suresh Venkatasubramanian.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/)###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast of 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).  Folklore from diverse parts of theoretical computer science is also often mentioned and explained, but unlike corridor discussions and asides in seminars, [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) can be searched and read at leisure.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, people have asked for more general advice from the community, on everything from [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic) to &quot;[how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).&quot;  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  Participation costs nothing but time.  _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting &#xD;&#xA;questions and answers, to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.  As one example, this announcement you are reading right now was written by a group of users on cstheory-Meta.  The site itself revolves around objective questions and specific answers.  Subjective discussions, unsubstantiated opinions, and general chit-chat are effectively discouraged by the site mechanisms.  Almost all active users are posting under their real names.  This has encouraged high-quality contributions and a constructive tone.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  We felt it was worth attempting to emulate the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow, and we are pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1337:  <row Id="1426" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="a82ebe89-da56-49a2-b33e-d2ff9f2298cf" CreationDate="2010-11-02T10:41:37.097" UserId="186" Comment="removing name" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Current contributors (please update)**: Dave Clarke, Lev Reyzin, Peter Shor, Aaron Sterling, Suresh Venkatasubramanian.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/)###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast of 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).  Folklore from diverse parts of theoretical computer science is also often mentioned and explained, but unlike corridor discussions and asides in seminars, [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) can be searched and read at leisure.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, people have asked for more general advice from the community, on everything from [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic) to &quot;[how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).&quot;  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  Participation costs nothing but time.  _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting &#xD;&#xA;questions and answers, to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.  As one example, this announcement you are reading right now was written by a group of users on cstheory-Meta.  The site itself revolves around objective questions and specific answers.  Subjective discussions, unsubstantiated opinions, and general chit-chat are effectively discouraged by the site mechanisms.  Almost all active users are posting under their real names.  This has encouraged high-quality contributions and a constructive tone.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  We felt it was worth attempting to emulate the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow, and we are pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1338:  <row Id="1427" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="d958bcf6-3128-4abb-a327-ae60a4ff3d10" CreationDate="2010-11-02T13:09:04.550" UserId="109" Comment="added suggestions by Peter Shor and arnab" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Current contributors (please update)**: Dave Clarke, Lev Reyzin, Peter Shor, Aaron Sterling, Suresh Venkatasubramanian.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/)###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast of 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).  Folklore from diverse parts of theoretical computer science is often mentioned and explained, but unlike corridor discussions and asides in seminars, [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) can be searched and read at leisure.  Some questions have also generated new proofs: Peter Shor demonstrated a reduction from Max-Cut with positive weights to a constant-factor approximation for the version of the problem with negative weights, Jukka Suomela demonstrated that DOMINATING SET remains NP-complete for planar bipartite graphs of maximum degree 3, and Per Vognsen outlined a proof for the Schwartz-Zippel Lemma using projective geometry.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, people have asked for more general advice from the community, on everything from [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic) to &quot;[how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).&quot;  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  Participation costs nothing but time.  _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting &#xD;&#xA;questions and answers, to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.  As one example, this announcement you are reading right now was written by a group of users on cstheory-Meta.  The site itself revolves around objective questions and specific answers.  Subjective discussions, unsubstantiated opinions, and general chit-chat are effectively discouraged by the site mechanisms.  Almost all active users are posting under their real names.  This has encouraged high-quality contributions and a constructive tone.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  We felt it was worth attempting to emulate the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow, and we are pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress" />
PostHistory.xml:1339:  <row Id="1428" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="f0654374-3105-457b-9812-e7c8c753ab3f" CreationDate="2010-11-02T14:11:59.003" UserId="109" Comment="add links" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Current contributors (please update)**: Dave Clarke, Lev Reyzin, Peter Shor, Aaron Sterling, Suresh Venkatasubramanian.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/)###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast of 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).  Folklore from diverse parts of theoretical computer science is often mentioned and explained, but unlike corridor discussions and asides in seminars, [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) can be searched and read at leisure.  Some questions have also generated new proofs: Peter Shor demonstrated a [reduction from Max-Cut with positive weights to a constant-factor approximation for the version of the problem with negative weights][3], Jukka Suomela demonstrated that [DOMINATING SET remains NP-complete for planar bipartite graphs of maximum degree 3][4], and Per Vognsen outlined a [proof for the Schwartz-Zippel Lemma using projective geometry][5].&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, people have asked for more general advice from the community, on everything from [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic) to &quot;[how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).&quot;  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  Participation costs nothing but time.  _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting &#xD;&#xA;questions and answers, to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.  As one example, this announcement you are reading right now was written by a group of users on cstheory-Meta.  The site itself revolves around objective questions and specific answers.  Subjective discussions, unsubstantiated opinions, and general chit-chat are effectively discouraged by the site mechanisms.  Almost all active users are posting under their real names.  This has encouraged high-quality contributions and a constructive tone.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  We felt it was worth attempting to emulate the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow, and we are pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress&#xD;&#xA;  [3]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2312/max-cut-with-negative-weight-edges/2318#2318&#xD;&#xA;  [4]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2505/is-the-dominating-set-problem-restricted-to-planar-bipartite-graphs-of-maximum-de/2508#2508&#xD;&#xA;  [5]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1772/alternative-proofs-of-schwartzzippel-lemma/1883#1883" />
