.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).  Folklore from diverse parts of theoretical computer science is often mentioned and explained, but unlike corridor discussions and asides in seminars, [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) can be searched and read at leisure.  Some questions have also generated new proofs: Peter Shor demonstrated a [reduction from Max-Cut with positive weights to a constant-factor approximation for the version of the problem with negative weights][3], Jukka Suomela demonstrated that [DOMINATING SET remains NP-complete for planar bipartite graphs of maximum degree 3][4], Sariel Har-Peled showed that [Hamiltonicity is NP-complete for k-regular graphs for any fixed k][5], and Per Vognsen outlined a [proof for the Schwartz-Zippel Lemma using projective geometry][6].&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, participants have asked for more general advice from the community, on everything from [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic) to &quot;[how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).&quot;  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  Participation costs nothing but time.  _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting &#xD;&#xA;questions and answers, to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.  As one example, this announcement you are reading right now was written by a group of users on cstheory-Meta.  The site itself revolves around objective questions and specific answers.  Subjective discussions, unsubstantiated opinions, and general chit-chat are effectively discouraged by the site mechanisms.  Almost all active users are posting under their real names.  This has encouraged high-quality contributions and a constructive tone.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  We felt it was worth attempting to emulate the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow, and we are pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress&#xD;&#xA;  [3]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2312/max-cut-with-negative-weight-edges/2318#2318&#xD;&#xA;  [4]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2505/is-the-dominating-set-problem-restricted-to-planar-bipartite-graphs-of-maximum-de/2508#2508&#xD;&#xA;  [5]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1651/hamiltonicity-of-k-regular-graphs/1656#1656&#xD;&#xA;  [6]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1772/alternative-proofs-of-schwartzzippel-lemma/1883#1883" />
