----------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/)###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast of 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.  Folklore from diverse parts of theoretical computer science is often mentioned and explained, but unlike corridor discussions and asides in seminars, [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) can be searched and read at leisure.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).  Some questions have also generated new proofs: Peter Shor demonstrated a [reduction from Max-Cut with positive weights to a constant-factor approximation for the version of the problem with negative weights][3], Jukka Suomela demonstrated that [DOMINATING SET remains NP-complete for planar bipartite graphs of maximum degree 3][4], Sariel Har-Peled showed that [Hamiltonicity is NP-complete for k-regular graphs for any fixed k][5], and Per Vognsen outlined a [proof for the Schwartz-Zippel Lemma using projective geometry][6].&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, participants have asked for more general advice from the community, on everything from [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic) to &quot;[how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).&quot;  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**. _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  Participation costs nothing but time. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting &#xD;&#xA;questions and answers, to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.  As one example, this announcement you are reading right now was written by a group of users on cstheory-Meta.  The site itself revolves around objective questions and specific answers.  Subjective discussions, unsubstantiated opinions, and general chit-chat are effectively discouraged by the site mechanisms.  Almost all active users are posting under their real names.  This has encouraged high-quality contributions and a constructive tone.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  We felt it was worth attempting to emulate the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow, and we are pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress&#xD;&#xA;  [3]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2312/max-cut-with-negative-weight-edges/2318#2318&#xD;&#xA;  [4]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2505/is-the-dominating-set-problem-restricted-to-planar-bipartite-graphs-of-maximum-de/2508#2508&#xD;&#xA;  [5]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1651/hamiltonicity-of-k-regular-graphs/1656#1656&#xD;&#xA;  [6]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1772/alternative-proofs-of-schwartzzippel-lemma/1883#1883" />
PostHistory.xml:1346:  <row Id="1435" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="c1bd1ea3-a305-498f-831f-a67669e85094" CreationDate="2010-11-02T20:00:52.720" UserId="30" Comment="made the language more journalistic, less standoffish, eg removed passive voice - matters of taste, not content" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Current contributors (please update)**: Dave Clarke, Lev Reyzin, Peter Shor, Aaron Sterling, Suresh Venkatasubramanian, David Eppstein.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit cstheory.stackexchange.com###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast of 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.  The atmosphere of the site is a bit like a corridor discussion at a conference: researchers discuss and explain both folklore and the newest results, in a format that can be read at leisure.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions have also generated new proofs: Peter Shor demonstrated a [reduction from Max-Cut with positive weights to a constant-factor approximation for the version of the problem with negative weights][3], Jukka Suomela demonstrated that [DOMINATING SET remains NP-complete for planar bipartite graphs of maximum degree 3][4], Sariel Har-Peled showed that [Hamiltonicity is NP-complete for k-regular graphs for any fixed k][5], and Per Vognsen outlined a [proof for the Schwartz-Zippel Lemma using projective geometry][6].&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, participants have asked for more general advice from the community, on everything from [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic) to &quot;[how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).&quot;  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**. _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  We encourage people to join and participate using their real names -- and almost everybody does this -- but it's not required.  Participation costs nothing but time. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting and a &quot;user reputation system,&quot; to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  We felt it was worth attempting to emulate the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow, and we are pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress&#xD;&#xA;  [3]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2312/max-cut-with-negative-weight-edges/2318#2318&#xD;&#xA;  [4]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2505/is-the-dominating-set-problem-restricted-to-planar-bipartite-graphs-of-maximum-de/2508#2508&#xD;&#xA;  [5]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1651/hamiltonicity-of-k-regular-graphs/1656#1656&#xD;&#xA;  [6]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1772/alternative-proofs-of-schwartzzippel-lemma/1883#1883" />
PostHistory.xml:1347:  <row Id="1436" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="04c8213f-04c1-4347-92fd-06dac9e79fec" CreationDate="2010-11-03T13:45:02.493" UserId="109" Comment="add another example of &quot;more than just answers&quot;" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Current contributors (please update)**: Dave Clarke, Lev Reyzin, Peter Shor, Aaron Sterling, Suresh Venkatasubramanian, David Eppstein.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit cstheory.stackexchange.com###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast of 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.  The atmosphere of the site is a bit like a corridor discussion at a conference: researchers discuss and explain both folklore and the newest results, in a format that can be read at leisure.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); Scott Aaronson summarized the [state-of-the-art in non-relativizing techniques][3]; and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions have also generated new proofs: Peter Shor demonstrated a [reduction from Max-Cut with positive weights to a constant-factor approximation for the version of the problem with negative weights][4], Jukka Suomela demonstrated that [DOMINATING SET remains NP-complete for planar bipartite graphs of maximum degree 3][5], Sariel Har-Peled showed that [Hamiltonicity is NP-complete for k-regular graphs for any fixed k][6], and Per Vognsen outlined a [proof for the Schwartz-Zippel Lemma using projective geometry][7].&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, participants have asked for more general advice from the community, on everything from [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic) to &quot;[how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).&quot;  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**. _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  We encourage people to join and participate using their real names -- and almost everybody does this -- but it's not required.  Participation costs nothing but time. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting and a &quot;user reputation system,&quot; to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  We felt it was worth attempting to emulate the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow, and we are pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress&#xD;&#xA;  [3]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2045/are-there-canonical-non-relativizing-techniques/2048#2048&#xD;&#xA;  [4]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2312/max-cut-with-negative-weight-edges/2318#2318&#xD;&#xA;  [5]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2505/is-the-dominating-set-problem-restricted-to-planar-bipartite-graphs-of-maximum-de/2508#2508&#xD;&#xA;  [6]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1651/hamiltonicity-of-k-regular-graphs/1656#1656&#xD;&#xA;  [7]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1772/alternative-proofs-of-schwartzzippel-lemma/1883#1883" />
PostHistory.xml:1348:  <row Id="1437" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="d8e382ce-07a4-4ddb-b265-25a89766cdc1" CreationDate="2010-11-03T13:50:07.357" UserId="109" Comment="add another soft question" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Current contributors (please update)**: Dave Clarke, Lev Reyzin, Peter Shor, Aaron Sterling, Suresh Venkatasubramanian, David Eppstein.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit cstheory.stackexchange.com###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast of 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.  The atmosphere of the site is a bit like a corridor discussion at a conference: researchers discuss and explain both folklore and the newest results, in a format that can be read at leisure.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); Scott Aaronson summarized the [state-of-the-art in non-relativizing techniques][3]; and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions have also generated new proofs: Peter Shor demonstrated a [reduction from Max-Cut with positive weights to a constant-factor approximation for the version of the problem with negative weights][4], Jukka Suomela demonstrated that [DOMINATING SET remains NP-complete for planar bipartite graphs of maximum degree 3][5], Sariel Har-Peled showed that [Hamiltonicity is NP-complete for k-regular graphs for any fixed k][6], and Per Vognsen outlined a [proof for the Schwartz-Zippel Lemma using projective geometry][7].&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, participants have asked for more general advice from the community, such as [how to referee papers][8], suggestions for [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic), and [how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**. _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  We encourage people to join and participate using their real names -- and almost everybody does this -- but it's not required.  Participation costs nothing but time. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting and a &quot;user reputation system,&quot; to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  We felt it was worth attempting to emulate the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow, and we are pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress&#xD;&#xA;  [3]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2045/are-there-canonical-non-relativizing-techniques/2048#2048&#xD;&#xA;  [4]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2312/max-cut-with-negative-weight-edges/2318#2318&#xD;&#xA;  [5]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2505/is-the-dominating-set-problem-restricted-to-planar-bipartite-graphs-of-maximum-de/2508#2508&#xD;&#xA;  [6]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1651/hamiltonicity-of-k-regular-graphs/1656#1656&#xD;&#xA;  [7]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1772/alternative-proofs-of-schwartzzippel-lemma/1883#1883&#xD;&#xA;  [8]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1893/how-do-i-referee-a-paper" />
PostHistory.xml:1349:  <row Id="1438" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="ea159919-d3fb-4b03-9bb0-afc7e0b8c8b8" CreationDate="2010-11-03T13:59:12.450" UserId="109" Comment="add another example of &quot;more than just answers&quot;" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Current contributors (please update)**: Dave Clarke, Lev Reyzin, Peter Shor, Aaron Sterling, Suresh Venkatasubramanian, David Eppstein.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit cstheory.stackexchange.com###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast of 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.  The atmosphere of the site is a bit like a corridor discussion at a conference: researchers discuss and explain both folklore and the newest results, in a format that can be read at leisure.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); Scott Aaronson summarized the [state-of-the-art in non-relativizing techniques][3]; Jeff Erickson explained why [the real RAM model is preferred in computational geometry][4]; and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions have also generated new proofs: Peter Shor demonstrated a [reduction from Max-Cut with positive weights to a constant-factor approximation for the version of the problem with negative weights][5], Jukka Suomela demonstrated that [DOMINATING SET remains NP-complete for planar bipartite graphs of maximum degree 3][6], Sariel Har-Peled showed that [Hamiltonicity is NP-complete for k-regular graphs for any fixed k][7], and Per Vognsen outlined a [proof for the Schwartz-Zippel Lemma using projective geometry][8].&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, participants have asked for more general advice from the community, such as [how to referee papers][9], suggestions for [Master's Thesis topics](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic), and [how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**. _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  We encourage people to join and participate using their real names -- and almost everybody does this -- but it's not required.  Participation costs nothing but time. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting and a &quot;user reputation system,&quot; to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  We felt it was worth attempting to emulate the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow, and we are pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress&#xD;&#xA;  [3]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2045/are-there-canonical-non-relativizing-techniques/2048#2048&#xD;&#xA;  [4]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2119/the-reasons-for-bss-real-ram-model-being-prefered-in-computational-geometry/2124#2124&#xD;&#xA;  [5]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2312/max-cut-with-negative-weight-edges/2318#2318&#xD;&#xA;  [6]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2505/is-the-dominating-set-problem-restricted-to-planar-bipartite-graphs-of-maximum-de/2508#2508&#xD;&#xA;  [7]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1651/hamiltonicity-of-k-regular-graphs/1656#1656&#xD;&#xA;  [8]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1772/alternative-proofs-of-schwartzzippel-lemma/1883#1883&#xD;&#xA;  [9]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1893/how-do-i-referee-a-paper" />
PostHistory.xml:1350:  <row Id="1439" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="0c1ee906-2e7d-412f-b459-e0f125e1e3bd" CreationDate="2010-11-03T14:13:57.600" UserId="109" Comment="add another soft question" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Current contributors (please update)**: Dave Clarke, Lev Reyzin, Peter Shor, Aaron Sterling, Suresh Venkatasubramanian, David Eppstein.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit cstheory.stackexchange.com###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast of 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.  The atmosphere of the site is a bit like a corridor discussion at a conference: researchers discuss and explain both folklore and the newest results, in a format that can be read at leisure.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); Scott Aaronson summarized the [state-of-the-art in non-relativizing techniques][3]; Jeff Erickson explained why [the real RAM model is preferred in computational geometry][4]; and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions have also generated new proofs: Peter Shor demonstrated a [reduction from Max-Cut with positive weights to a constant-factor approximation for the version of the problem with negative weights][5], Jukka Suomela demonstrated that [DOMINATING SET remains NP-complete for planar bipartite graphs of maximum degree 3][6], Sariel Har-Peled showed that [Hamiltonicity is NP-complete for k-regular graphs for any fixed k][7], and Per Vognsen outlined a [proof for the Schwartz-Zippel Lemma using projective geometry][8].&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, participants have asked for more general advice from the community, such as [how to referee papers][9], possible [Master's thesis topics in automata theory](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic), suggestions for an [inspirational talk about theoretical computer science][10], and [how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**. _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  We encourage people to join and participate using their real names -- and almost everybody does this -- but it's not required.  Participation costs nothing but time. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting and a &quot;user reputation system,&quot; to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  We felt it was worth attempting to emulate the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow, and we are pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress&#xD;&#xA;  [3]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2045/are-there-canonical-non-relativizing-techniques/2048#2048&#xD;&#xA;  [4]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2119/the-reasons-for-bss-real-ram-model-being-prefered-in-computational-geometry/2124#2124&#xD;&#xA;  [5]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2312/max-cut-with-negative-weight-edges/2318#2318&#xD;&#xA;  [6]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2505/is-the-dominating-set-problem-restricted-to-planar-bipartite-graphs-of-maximum-de/2508#2508&#xD;&#xA;  [7]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1651/hamiltonicity-of-k-regular-graphs/1656#1656&#xD;&#xA;  [8]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1772/alternative-proofs-of-schwartzzippel-lemma/1883#1883&#xD;&#xA;  [9]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1893/how-do-i-referee-a-paper&#xD;&#xA;  [10]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2386/inspirational-talk-for-final-year-high-school-pupils/2411#2411" />
PostHistory.xml:1351:  <row Id="1440" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="583" RevisionGUID="d47a0c56-7d6d-495a-bfa6-9f6bb418ecf9" CreationDate="2010-11-03T14:29:37.230" UserId="123" Comment="demonstrated --&gt; gave, so we dont have two &quot;demonstrated&quot;s in a row" Text="Hi all,&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  I chatted with Lance Fortnow at FOCS about the various ideas I brought up in [my answer][1] to &quot;[Beta period progress][2]&quot;. This &quot;question&quot; is about the first, namely: &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; Write a note in SIGACT News&#xD;&#xA;&gt; advertising the site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I was thinking (and maybe this is too pie-in-the-sky) that this post could be written jointly by the community, by editing this very post (I'll put a crude skeleton in place). The article, when published, could be attributed to the website &quot;with contributions from&quot; anyone who helped edit the post (but only real names, please). &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I'd like to make a few requests though:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; 1. Use an answer to discuss a particular aspect of the article. I understand that issues will overlap, but it's easier to track answers than have one giant comment thread below this question&#xD;&#xA; 2. Make sure you use your real name when editing. We can use revision history to determine who changed what. &#xD;&#xA; 3. I think it's also fair to assume that simple edits (syntax, spelling) are not at the contribution level that might merit &quot;with contributions from&quot;, so try to focus on content edits, and we can all chip in to fix minor issues. &#xD;&#xA; 4. If you want to discuss whether we should be doing this at all, a different question might be a better place for that. Frankly, I don't see a downside. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Current contributors (please update)**: Dave Clarke, Lev Reyzin, Peter Shor, Aaron Sterling, Suresh Venkatasubramanian, David Eppstein.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask a group of professionals what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2379/refereed-games-with-uncorrelated-semi-private-coins).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit cstheory.stackexchange.com###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently, the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast of 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.  The atmosphere of the site is a bit like a corridor discussion at a conference: researchers discuss and explain both folklore and the newest results, in a format that can be read at leisure.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than &quot;just answers&quot;: they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;commonsense explanation&quot; for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); Scott Aaronson summarized the [state-of-the-art in non-relativizing techniques][3]; Jeff Erickson explained why [the real RAM model is preferred in computational geometry][4]; and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions have also generated new proofs: Peter Shor gave a [reduction from Max-Cut with positive weights to a constant-factor approximation for the version of the problem with negative weights][5], Jukka Suomela demonstrated that [DOMINATING SET remains NP-complete for planar bipartite graphs of maximum degree 3][6], Sariel Har-Peled showed that [Hamiltonicity is NP-complete for k-regular graphs for any fixed k][7], and Per Vognsen outlined a [proof for the Schwartz-Zippel Lemma using projective geometry][8].&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions by both students and top experts, participants have asked for more general advice from the community, such as [how to referee papers][9], possible [Master's thesis topics in automata theory](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic), suggestions for an [inspirational talk about theoretical computer science][10], and [how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).  The overall scope of the site is **Research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**. _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  We encourage people to join and participate using their real names -- and almost everybody does this -- but it's not required.  Participation costs nothing but time. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###About StackExchange###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is a new member of the StackExchange family of websites, which also includes the well-known StackOverflow.com (devoted to programming) and&#xD;&#xA;MathOverflow.org (devoted to research-level mathematics).  The StackExchange software provides mechanisms, such as up- or down-voting and a &quot;user reputation system,&quot; to highlight and encourage excellent questions and answers, and to control spam.  There is also a &quot;Meta&quot; area, for discussions about site scope and direction.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Many of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution of the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate areas from around the world.  It became clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  We felt it was worth attempting to emulate the site format (and the question-and-answer policy) of the successful MathOverflow, and we are pleased by the results so far.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress&#xD;&#xA;  [3]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2045/are-there-canonical-non-relativizing-techniques/2048#2048&#xD;&#xA;  [4]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2119/the-reasons-for-bss-real-ram-model-being-prefered-in-computational-geometry/2124#2124&#xD;&#xA;  [5]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2312/max-cut-with-negative-weight-edges/2318#2318&#xD;&#xA;  [6]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2505/is-the-dominating-set-problem-restricted-to-planar-bipartite-graphs-of-maximum-de/2508#2508&#xD;&#xA;  [7]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1651/hamiltonicity-of-k-regular-graphs/1656#1656&#xD;&#xA;  [8]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1772/alternative-proofs-of-schwartzzippel-lemma/1883#1883&#xD;&#xA;  [9]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1893/how-do-i-referee-a-paper&#xD;&#xA;  [10]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2386/inspirational-talk-for-final-year-high-school-pupils/2411#2411" />
