n (Mountain time). At that point I'll take the text and links, convert to latex-ized PDF, and send it off to the SIGACT News Editor. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**More updates**. I'm now locking this post, since it's Friday @ Noon here in Utah. I'll start doing the latexing, and will link to a PDF shortly. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**PDF Update**: [Here's a link to the PDF][3], with the citation format taken from [this meta discussion][4]. I have emailed this version to [Brendan Mumey][5] (SIGACT News editor)&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions Answered. In theory.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    cstheory.stackexchange.com&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Questions Answered.  In Theory.###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Perhaps you're a computer scientist wondering [how much the Axiom of Choice matters to the theorems you study and prove](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/which-interesting-theorems-in-tcs-rely-on-the-axiom-of-choice-or-alternatively).  Perhaps you're a mathematician who needs [a top expert to explain what &quot;randomness&quot; really means in computability and complexity](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1263/truly-random-number-generator-turing-computable).  Perhaps you need [a list of problems that can be used to show polynomial-time hardness results, to strengthen your toolkit of reductions](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1284/problems-that-can-be-used-to-show-polynomial-time-hardness-results/).  Or perhaps you think a problem might be open -- but might just as easily be solved -- so [you'd like to ask](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2708/complexity-of-greatest-common-divisor-gcd/2713) a group of professionals [what they think](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2461/interactive-proofs-for-levels-of-the-polynomial-hierarchy).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Visit cstheory.stackexchange.com###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) provides this interaction &quot;at the speed of the internet,&quot; by bringing together researchers from around the world, and across the broad spectrum of theoretical computer science.  Active participants range from advanced undergraduates to well-established scientists. Currently the majority of participants are graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, but the number of senior researchers active within the site is growing quickly.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Even though [cs.theory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) is only two months old, it can already boast of 2,000 registered users, 700 answered questions, and -- perhaps most exciting -- [new research collaborations among computer scientists](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2328/when-should-you-say-what-you-know/2362#2362) who otherwise might never have realized that they were working on related problems.  The atmosphere of the site is a bit like a corridor discussion at a conference: researchers discuss and explain both folklore and the newest results, in a format that can be read at leisure.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some questions and their answers are highly technical, but the answers from experts are often more than just answers; they contain insights that are not available in papers or textbooks.  For example, a student who requested a &quot;common sense&quot; explanation for how padding arguments related to complexity class separations received [an intuitive answer from Russell Impagliazzo](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2434/why-do-complexity-classes-translate-upwards-and-not-downwards/2453#2453); Scott Aaronson summarized the [state-of-the-art in non-relativizing techniques][6]; Jeff Erickson explained why [the real RAM model is preferred in computational geometry][7]; and a student who asked whether the Nisan-Wigderson pseudorandom number generator relativizes received [an answer from Noam Nisan](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2236/does-nisans-pseudo-random-generator-relativize/2239#2239).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Questions have also generated new proofs: Peter Shor gave a [reduction from Max-Cut with positive weights to a constant-factor approximation for the version of the problem with negative weights][8]; Jukka Suomela demonstrated that [DOMINATING SET remains NP-complete for planar bipartite graphs of maximum degree 3][9]; Sariel Har-Peled showed that [Hamiltonicity is NP-complete for k-regular graphs for any fixed k][10]; and Per Vognsen outlined a [proof for the Schwartz-Zippel Lemma using projective geometry][11].&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In addition to specific technical questions, participants have asked for more general advice from the community, such as [how to referee papers][12], possible [Master's thesis topics in automata theory](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/979/automata-theory-formal-language-thesis-topic), pointers to [recent purely functional data structures][13], suggestions for an [inspirational talk about theoretical computer science][14], and [how to find a job](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2215/how-to-get-a-job).  The site is a place for the larger theory community to come together.  The overall scope of the site is **research-level theoretical computer science, broadly defined**.  _Note that homework questions are not allowed on the site_.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Everyone with a research interest in theoretical computer science is welcome to create an account.  We encourage participation using real names -- and almost everybody does this -- but it's not required.  Participation costs nothing, and takes as little or as much time as you choose. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Site Origin and Structure###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some of the founding members of [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/) participated in discussion of a proposed solution to the P/NP problem that spanned multiple blogs, led to the creation of wiki pages, and brought together researchers in disparate fields from around the world.  This effort made it clear that the worldwide theoretical computer science community was ready for -- and needed -- a structured way to ask research-level questions and to consider answers to such questions.  The success of MathOverflow.net (a site devoted to research-level mathematics) encouraged us to adopt the StackExchange software developed by Jeff Atwood and Joel Spolsky. This software provides a user reputation system built on up- and down-voting of contributions to highlight and encourage high quality, and to control spam.  There is also a [&quot;Meta&quot; area][15], for discussions about site scope and direction. Thus far, the system has worked extremely well and we are very pleased with it. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;###Who runs the site?###&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;You do ! The site is moderated by the community, with users gaining access to more management tools as they gain more reputation within the site. We have an active core of users who diligently monitor the site, help improve the quality of questions and answers, and filter out spam. In fact, this very article is a product of community participation on the site. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;But you don't have to worry about any of that to contribute to the numerous research discussions taking place right now. Please visit -- and participate in! -- [cstheory.stackexchange.com](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/), the 24/7/365 gathering-place for theoretical computer scientists from around the world to share information and insights.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;  [1]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress/526#526&#xD;&#xA;  [2]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/522/beta-period-progress&#xD;&#xA;  [3]: http://www.cs.utah.edu/~suresh/cstheory.pdf&#xD;&#xA;  [4]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/352/how-will-you-cite-a-discussion-on-this-site-in-your-paper&#xD;&#xA;  [5]: http://www.cs.montana.edu/mumey/www/Home.html&#xD;&#xA;  [6]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2045/are-there-canonical-non-relativizing-techniques/2048#2048&#xD;&#xA;  [7]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2119/the-reasons-for-bss-real-ram-model-being-prefered-in-computational-geometry/2124#2124&#xD;&#xA;  [8]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2312/max-cut-with-negative-weight-edges/2318#2318&#xD;&#xA;  [9]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2505/is-the-dominating-set-problem-restricted-to-planar-bipartite-graphs-of-maximum-de/2508#2508&#xD;&#xA;  [10]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1651/hamiltonicity-of-k-regular-graphs/1656#1656&#xD;&#xA;  [11]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1772/alternative-proofs-of-schwartzzippel-lemma/1883#1883&#xD;&#xA;  [12]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1893/how-do-i-referee-a-paper&#xD;&#xA;  [13]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/1539/whats-new-in-purely-functional-data-structures-since-okasaki&#xD;&#xA;  [14]: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/2386/inspirational-talk-for-final-year-high-school-pupils/2411#2411&#xD;&#xA;  [15]: http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/" />
PostHistory.xml:1416:  <row Id="1507" PostHistoryTypeId="2" PostId="624" RevisionGUID="9335c434-cbb1-448c-b919-2b904a741df4" CreationDate="2010-11-07T22:37:10.357" UserId="186" Text="I. This is not a \*\***research-level**\*\* question in theoretical computer science as defined in the scope and is too elementary for this site (perhaps a homework exercise). Please see \[\]() and read the FAQ.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;II. This site is for \*\***research-level questions**\*\* in \*\***theoretical computer science**\*\*, that are likely to have short well-defined answers. &quot;Research-level&quot; means, roughly, questions that might be discussed between two professors, or between graduate students working on Ph.D.'s, but not usually between a professor and the typical undergraduate student. It does not include questions at the level of difficulty of undergraduate homework. You can try Math.SE (elementary math/theory) or StackOverflow (programming)." />
PostHistory.xml:1417:  <row Id="1508" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="235" RevisionGUID="24eb3508-1a8a-484e-9e08-002c4c02572a" CreationDate="2010-11-07T22:58:24.253" UserId="567" Comment="added the “research-level” constraint and a link to math.stackexchange.com" Text="What kind of questions are too basic?&#xD;&#xA;-------------------------------------&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Our aim is to ask and answer _research-level_ questions in theoretical computer science.  Here are examples of questions that are off-topic because they are &quot;too easy&quot;:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; - Questions that can be easily answered by reading a Wikipedia article on the topic.&#xD;&#xA; - Questions that can be easily solved by Googling.&#xD;&#xA; - Questions that are solved by browsing [one of these web sites](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/225/official-faq-for-theoretical-computer-science/229#229).&#xD;&#xA; - Typical homework problems in textbooks.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;If you do not think that your question is research-level but you cannot find an answer in above options, you may want to try http://math.stackexchange.com/.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;---&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Related discussion:&#xD;&#xA;[[1]](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/17/scope-of-questions)&#xD;&#xA;[[2]](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/115/what-level-and-types-of-questions-are-appropriate-for-theoretical-computer-scienc)&#xD;&#xA;[[3]](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/209/homework-or-things-that-look-like-homework)" />
PostHistory.xml:1429:  <row Id="1520" PostHistoryTypeId="2" PostId="631" RevisionGUID="289e436c-81eb-4604-b980-b90db932af8b" CreationDate="2010-11-08T00:52:27.213" UserId="567" Text="While our aim is to ask and answer _research-level_ questions, we would like to be helpful to those who do not know where to ask non-research-level questions.  One way is probably to suggest alternate ways to get an answer to such a question.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Here I would specifically gather the information about:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; **Question**.  On which websites can people ask non-research-level questions in theoretical computer science?&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Since we do not want to flood other websites which do not like non-research-level questions in TCS, I appreciate if you can provide some evidence that the website is really appropriate for such questions.&#xD;&#xA;" />
