PostHistory.xml:2477:  <row Id="2651" PostHistoryTypeId="2" PostId="1093" RevisionGUID="9737f670-674b-49d0-96eb-77675e82c291" CreationDate="2011-04-03T11:30:22.967" UserId="873" Text="While a person can become a pro in one topic, it is not possible to master all the fields; even if we narrow it doe to computer science. Interdisciplinary fields make the problem worst. For instance, someone who works in (theoretical, not applied) cryptography must have a good knowledge of the computational complexity.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;What happens when you need to ask a question which, while related to your research topic, happens to be lie within another field? Well, a complicated problem for you might be too basic for researches in the target field.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I like the model of Math.SE / MathOverflow a lot: If I think my question is too basic (which usually is!), I'll ask it on Math.SE. Research-level questions can be asked on the latter.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;This discussion has recently gained momentum on Area51; here are some links:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* Two level model (MO/Math.SE) vs one level model (SO) ([Google cache](http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:a0T-87gEWJ8J:discuss.area51.stackexchange.com/questions/612/two-level-model-mo-math-se-vs-one-level-model-so+http://discuss.area51.stackexchange.com/questions/612/two-level-model-mo-math-se-vs-one-level-model-so&amp;cd=1&amp;hl=en&amp;ct=clnk&amp;source=www.google.com) version)&#xD;&#xA;* What problems does the two-level split solve ([Google cache](http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:JI_t5OZKMWYJ:discuss.area51.stackexchange.com/questions/630/what-problems-does-the-two-level-split-solve+http://discuss.area51.stackexchange.com/questions/630/what-problems-does-the-two-level-split-solve&amp;cd=1&amp;hl=en&amp;ct=clnk&amp;source=www.google.com) version)&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;And even proposals like **Beginner Theoretical Computer Science** or **Computer Science** were  considered; but they were soon deleted/closed due to lack of support / misunderstanding that they are exact duplicates of other SE sites.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Lack of Support:** I believe that such proposals did not advertise themselves well. For instance, if I ever knew that they exist, I'd join them at once. This is the main reason I'm raising the issue here.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Exact Duplicates:** Some of the voters (to close) claimed that such proposals are exact duplicates of StackOverflow, while others claim that they are exact duplicates of TCS.SE. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* The former group believed that anything in computer science which is not theoretical is programming related. In my opinion, that is plain wrong. A basic question about Turing machines is a simple counterexample.&#xD;&#xA;* The latter group where unable to distinguish between research-level questions and basic ones.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some discussions can be found here: [Is Computer Science a duplicate of Theoretical Computer Science](http://discuss.area51.stackexchange.com/q/682/22946).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In an extreme case, Jonik suggested: &quot;Instead of another site, how about modifying the description of the existing site to allow a little less advanced CS theory questions too.&quot; His suggestion was unwelcome, and received some down-votes. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In another thread, &#xD;&#xA;Joel Spolsky [requested](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/947/873) that we (TCS.SE) broaden our view. His suggestion didn't go anywhere either.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; **The bottom line:** I believe that CSTheory must have a non-research-level counterpart. I ask people here to help (re)create one on Area51, and support it adequately.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;PS: There's always an issue of homeworks: Professors don't like their students to *cheat* by asking homework problems in online forums. This can be handled as in Math.SE, or by developing adequate policies at the new site." />
PostHistory.xml:2481:  <row Id="2655" PostHistoryTypeId="2" PostId="1095" RevisionGUID="cb2dc59b-4ba0-4adc-a0f8-584bc5d67b99" CreationDate="2011-04-03T14:02:36.363" UserId="634" Text="[The official answer is Stack Overflow.](http://meta.stackoverflow.com/questions/80023/where-on-se-to-discuss-computer-science/80058#80058)&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;No, this doesn't make any sense to me either.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[A previous proposal for a CS site was shot down in the bud.](http://area51.stackexchange.com/proposals/29282/computer-science) I suspect the closers considered it a duplicate of TCS, rather than SO (there's a widespread ill-informed impression that widening TCS to include non-research question would be a small shift in scope). This happened even though the proposal clearly stated the difference between this site and the proposed site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Unfortunately, if you create a new CS proposal on Area 51, it'll probably rightly be closed as a duplicate of the original. Five [people with at least 2000 rep on Area 51](http://area51.stackexchange.com/users?tab=reputation) can vote to reopen the [original](http://area51.stackexchange.com/proposals/29282/computer-science).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Having a Stack Exchange site about computer science looks like it means changing Jeff's mind. So the most likely route would be a different platform and hosting. Which is sad, because having shared accounts and migration paths between SO, CS and TCS would make a lot of sense.&#xD;&#xA;" />
PostHistory.xml:2483:  <row Id="2657" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="1095" RevisionGUID="22ac9e4d-8ff3-4032-8529-c678bfd974c1" CreationDate="2011-04-03T20:43:15.777" UserId="634" Comment="added 143 characters in body" Text="[The official answer is Stack Overflow.](http://meta.stackoverflow.com/questions/80023/where-on-se-to-discuss-computer-science/80058#80058)&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;No, this doesn't make any sense to me either.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;[A previous proposal for a CS site was shot down in the bud.](http://area51.stackexchange.com/proposals/29282/computer-science) I suspect the closers considered it a duplicate of TCS, rather than SO (there's a widespread ill-informed impression that widening TCS to include non-research question would be a small shift in scope, combined with [opposition to a research-only site](http://meta.stackoverflow.com/questions/79351/should-research-level-only-sites-be-allowed)). This happened even though the proposal clearly stated the difference between this site and the proposed site.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Unfortunately, if you create a new CS proposal on Area 51, it'll probably rightly be closed as a duplicate of the original. Five [people with at least 2000 rep on Area 51](http://area51.stackexchange.com/users?tab=reputation) can vote to reopen the [original](http://area51.stackexchange.com/proposals/29282/computer-science).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Having a Stack Exchange site about computer science looks like it means changing Jeff's mind. So the most likely route would be a different platform and hosting. Which is sad, because having shared accounts and migration paths between SO, CS and TCS would make a lot of sense.&#xD;&#xA;" />
PostHistory.xml:2484:  <row Id="2658" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="1093" RevisionGUID="a32b7c31-834e-4b82-81f6-6d67c9b901bc" CreationDate="2011-04-03T21:17:52.673" UserId="237" Comment="Restored Area 51 discussions and moved the referenced links back to the 'live' discussion." Text="While a person can become a pro in one topic, it is not possible to master all the fields; even if we narrow it doe to computer science. Interdisciplinary fields make the problem worst. For instance, someone who works in (theoretical, not applied) cryptography must have a good knowledge of the computational complexity.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;What happens when you need to ask a question which, while related to your research topic, happens to be lie within another field? Well, a complicated problem for you might be too basic for researches in the target field.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I like the model of Math.SE / MathOverflow a lot: If I think my question is too basic (which usually is!), I'll ask it on Math.SE. Research-level questions can be asked on the latter.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;This discussion has recently gained momentum on Area51; here are some links:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* [Two level model (MO/Math.SE) vs one level model (SO)](http://discuss.area51.stackexchange.com/questions/612/two-level-model-mo-math-se-vs-one-level-model-so)&#xD;&#xA;* [What problems does the two-level split solve](http://discuss.area51.stackexchange.com/questions/630/what-problems-does-the-two-level-split-solve)&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;And even proposals like **Beginner Theoretical Computer Science** or **Computer Science** were  considered; but they were soon deleted/closed due to lack of support / misunderstanding that they are exact duplicates of other SE sites.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Lack of Support:** I believe that such proposals did not advertise themselves well. For instance, if I ever knew that they exist, I'd join them at once. This is the main reason I'm raising the issue here.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Exact Duplicates:** Some of the voters (to close) claimed that such proposals are exact duplicates of StackOverflow, while others claim that they are exact duplicates of TCS.SE. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* The former group believed that anything in computer science which is not theoretical is programming related. In my opinion, that is plain wrong. A basic question about Turing machines is a simple counterexample.&#xD;&#xA;* The latter group where unable to distinguish between research-level questions and basic ones.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some discussions can be found here: [Is Computer Science a duplicate of Theoretical Computer Science](http://discuss.area51.stackexchange.com/q/682/22946).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In an extreme case, Jonik suggested: &quot;Instead of another site, how about modifying the description of the existing site to allow a little less advanced CS theory questions too.&quot; His suggestion was unwelcome, and received some down-votes. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In another thread, &#xD;&#xA;Joel Spolsky [requested](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/947/873) that we (TCS.SE) broaden our view. His suggestion didn't go anywhere either.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; **The bottom line:** I believe that CSTheory must have a non-research-level counterpart. I ask people here to help (re)create one on Area51, and support it adequately.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;PS: There's always an issue of homeworks: Professors don't like their students to *cheat* by asking homework problems in online forums. This can be handled as in Math.SE, or by developing adequate policies at the new site." />
PostHistory.xml:2486:  <row Id="2660" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="1093" RevisionGUID="e2ce5f3a-9b5b-4a80-a551-de46afc3fe36" CreationDate="2011-04-04T11:37:12.200" UserId="873" Comment="deleted 4 characters in body; deleted 1 characters in body" Text="While a person can become a pro in one topic, it is not possible to master all the fields; even if we narrow it to computer science. Interdisciplinary fields make the problem worse. For instance, someone who works in (theoretical, not applied) cryptography must have a good knowledge of the computational complexity.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;What happens when you need to ask a question which, while related to your research topic, happens to be lie within another field? Well, a complicated problem for you might be too basic for researches in the target field.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I like the model of Math.SE / MathOverflow a lot: If I think my question is too basic (which usually is!), I'll ask it on Math.SE. Research-level questions can be asked on the latter.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;This discussion has recently gained momentum on Area51; here are some links:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* [Two level model (MO/Math.SE) vs one level model (SO)](http://discuss.area51.stackexchange.com/questions/612/two-level-model-mo-math-se-vs-one-level-model-so)&#xD;&#xA;* [What problems does the two-level split solve](http://discuss.area51.stackexchange.com/questions/630/what-problems-does-the-two-level-split-solve)&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;And even proposals like **Beginner Theoretical Computer Science** or **Computer Science** were  considered; but they were soon deleted/closed due to lack of support / misunderstanding that they are exact duplicates of other SE sites.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Lack of Support:** I believe that such proposals did not advertise themselves well. For instance, if I ever knew that they exist, I'd join them at once. This is the main reason I'm raising the issue here.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;**Exact Duplicates:** Some of the voters (to close) claimed that such proposals are exact duplicates of StackOverflow, while others claim that they are exact duplicates of TCS.SE. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* The former group believed that anything in computer science which is not theoretical is programming related. In my opinion, that is plain wrong. A basic question about Turing machines is a simple counterexample.&#xD;&#xA;* The latter group were unable to distinguish between research-level questions and basic ones.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Some discussions can be found here: [Is Computer Science a duplicate of Theoretical Computer Science](http://discuss.area51.stackexchange.com/q/682/22946).&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In an extreme case, Jonik suggested: &quot;Instead of another site, how about modifying the description of the existing site to allow a little less advanced CS theory questions too.&quot; His suggestion was unwelcome, and received some down-votes. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In another thread, &#xD;&#xA;Joel Spolsky [requested](http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/947/873) that we (TCS.SE) broaden our view. His suggestion didn't go anywhere either.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt; **The bottom line:** I believe that CSTheory must have a non-research-level counterpart. I ask people here to help (re)create one on Area51, and support it adequately.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;PS: There's always an issue of homeworks: Professors don't like their students to *cheat* by asking homework problems in online forums. This can be handled as in Math.SE, or by developing adequate policies at the new site." />
