PostHistory.xml:4034:  <row Id="5330" PostHistoryTypeId="8" PostId="2700" RevisionGUID="2da3d5ce-c05f-447a-9e1a-e1fec4ae908f" CreationDate="2013-07-25T22:25:18.197" UserId="186" Comment="Rollback to [a97401e3-641c-4a45-88c9-086b918c5522]" Text="###Not research-level:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&gt;Questions does not appear to be a **research-level** question in theoretical computer science.  For more information, please see [scope](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/help/on-topic)." />
PostHistory.xml:4039:  <row Id="5335" PostHistoryTypeId="2" PostId="2712" RevisionGUID="80ae29f9-1672-484f-b74d-76425124f9c2" CreationDate="2013-08-02T21:07:24.483" UserId="5038" Text="I have a request.  Could folks here be just a little more careful about what questions they migrate to CS.SE?&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I noticed recently a few low-quality questions that were migrated to the Computer Science Stack Exchange (CS.SE) site.  I'd like to ask people to try to be careful not to migrate low-quality questions.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* If it's a good question, and on-topic for CS.SE, I definitely encourage you to migrate to CS.SE.  For instance, if it is not research-level but would be a reasonable question, migrating to CS.SE is a great idea.  Go for it!&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* But if it's a bad question -- one that would be a bad question for CS.SE -- please don't migrate it to CS.SE.  If it's a bad question, just close it, don't migrate it.  Please don't make CS.SE a dumping ground for bad questions.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Do note that migration requires you to be familiar with the expectations and norms of the target site (CS.SE, in this case).  If you are not active on CS.SE or not confident that you are familiar with what sort of questions are encouraged at CS.SE, it might be better to avoid voting on whether to migrate questions to CS.SE, and instead just vote to close the question.  For instance, we should not be migrating questions that are duplicates or that are already covered by the standard reference questions on CS.SE; if you're not familiar with what those cover, you might want to consider carefully before voting on whether to migrate or not.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;One recent example: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/18536/5038.  In my opinion, that question shouldn't have been migrated to CS.SE.  It is not a good fit for the Computer Science Stack Exchange.  The question  does not show evidence of effort.  It asks a question about a topic that is already covered by reference questions at CS.SE, with no evidence that the question-asker was aware of that.  Of course, that's just one example.  I don't mean to pick on that one or focus on that one too much.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;And I don't mean to imply that this is a huge, systemic problem that requires major changes to migration.  Overall I think the process is generally working well.  I'm just asking folks to be mindful about when to migrate and when not to migrate.  Thank you for listening!&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Related:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/1086/5038&#xD;&#xA;* http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/1285/5038&#xD;&#xA;* http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/1507/5038" />
PostHistory.xml:4043:  <row Id="5339" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="2712" RevisionGUID="6c36bf05-3be5-4ee4-b38e-b29c187e5f96" CreationDate="2013-08-02T22:02:43.620" UserId="5038" Comment="elaborate." Text="I have a request.  It would be nice if the moderators here would avoid migrating low-quality questions to CS.SE.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I noticed recently a few low-quality questions that were migrated to the Computer Science Stack Exchange (CS.SE) site.  I would suggest that we avoid doing that.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* If it's a good question, and on-topic for CS.SE, I definitely encourage you to migrate to CS.SE.  For instance, if it is not research-level but would be a reasonable question, migrating to CS.SE is a great idea.  Go for it!&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* But if it's a bad question -- one that would be a bad question for CS.SE -- please don't migrate it to CS.SE.  If it's a bad question, just close it, don't migrate it.  Please don't make CS.SE a dumping ground for bad questions.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* If it's a good question -- well-researched, on-topic, focused, narrow -- but has some English/grammar problems, don't let that stop you from migrating.  If it's just the English, we can edit it over at CS.SE.  But if it is a fundamentally bad question -- e.g., not well-researched, or a duplicate, or unclear -- I personally don't think it should be migrated over to CS.SE&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;One recent example: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/18536/5038.  In my opinion, that question shouldn't have been migrated to CS.SE.  It is not a good fit for the Computer Science Stack Exchange.  The question does not show evidence of effort.  It asks a question about a topic that is already covered by reference questions at CS.SE, with no evidence that the question-asker was aware of that.  These issues are not something that those of us at CS.SE can fix through simple edits to the question.  Of course, that's just one example.  I don't mean to pick on that one or focus on that one too much.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Kaveh explains that the CS.SE admins specifically requested that &quot;badly written&quot; questions are still OK to migrate to CS.SE.  I didn't realize that!  That explains a lot.  Perhaps that's something we should discuss.  I'm not sure whether &quot;badly written&quot; refers to the English/grammar, or to more fundamental issues (like whether it's a good question, whether it is well-researched, whether it is on-topic and focused and detailed and not a duplicate).  If the former, I agree, English/grammar problems should not be a barrier to migration.  If the latter, well, I guess I might have a slight difference of opinion with the CS.SE admins -- maybe that's something we need to discuss on CS.meta, instead of here.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I certainly don't mean to imply that this is a huge, systemic problem that requires major changes to migration, and I don't mean to imply the moderators here are doing anything wrong (I think the moderators are doing a great job!).  Overall I think the process is generally working well.  I just wanted to suggest a minor refinement that I think might make things work better on CS.SE.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Related:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/1086/5038&#xD;&#xA;* http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/1285/5038&#xD;&#xA;* http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/1507/5038" />
PostHistory.xml:4045:  <row Id="5341" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="2712" RevisionGUID="de8cbb3e-d503-4819-a530-45439b24a7a5" CreationDate="2013-08-02T22:25:24.073" UserId="5038" Comment="added 108 characters in body" Text="I have a request.  It would be nice if the moderators here would avoid migrating low-quality questions to CS.SE.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I noticed recently a few low-quality questions that were migrated to the Computer Science Stack Exchange (CS.SE) site.  I would suggest that we avoid doing that.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* If it's a good question, and on-topic for CS.SE, I definitely encourage you to migrate to CS.SE.  For instance, if it is not research-level but would be a reasonable question, migrating to CS.SE is a great idea.  Go for it!&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* But if it's a bad question -- one that would be a bad question for CS.SE -- please don't migrate it to CS.SE.  If it's a bad question, just close it, don't migrate it.  Please don't make CS.SE a dumping ground for bad questions.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* If it's a good question -- well-researched, on-topic, focused, narrow -- but has some English/grammar problems, don't let that stop you from migrating.  If it's just the English, we can edit it over at CS.SE.  But if it is a fundamentally bad question -- e.g., not well-researched, or a duplicate, or unclear -- I personally don't think it should be migrated over to CS.SE&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;One recent example: http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/18536/5038.  In my opinion, that question shouldn't have been migrated to CS.SE.  It is not a good fit for the Computer Science Stack Exchange.  The question does not show evidence of effort.  It asks a question about a topic that is already covered by reference questions at CS.SE, with no evidence that the question-asker was aware of that.  These issues are not something that those of us at CS.SE can fix through simple edits to the question.  Of course, that's just one example.  I don't mean to pick on that one or focus on that one too much.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Kaveh explains that the CS.SE admins specifically requested that &quot;badly written&quot; questions are still OK to migrate to CS.SE.  I didn't realize that!  That explains a lot.  Perhaps that's something we should discuss.  I'm not sure whether &quot;badly written&quot; refers to the English/grammar, or to more fundamental issues (like whether it's a good question, whether it is well-researched, whether it is on-topic and focused and detailed and not a duplicate).  If the former, I agree, English/grammar problems should not be a barrier to migration.  If the latter, well, I guess I might have a slight difference of opinion with the CS.SE admins -- maybe that's something we need to discuss on CS.meta, instead of here.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I certainly don't mean to imply that this is a huge, systemic problem that requires major changes to migration, and I don't mean to imply the moderators here are doing anything wrong (I think the moderators are doing a great job!).  Overall I think the process is generally working well.  I just wanted to suggest a minor refinement that I think might make things work better on CS.SE.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;Related:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;* http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/1086/5038&#xD;&#xA;* http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/1285/5038&#xD;&#xA;* http://meta.cstheory.stackexchange.com/q/1507/5038&#xD;&#xA;* [Do we want CSTheory.SE to migrate bad questions over here?](http://meta.cs.stackexchange.com/q/691/755)" />
PostHistory.xml:4046:  <row Id="5342" PostHistoryTypeId="2" PostId="2714" RevisionGUID="213ed5dd-6eba-4f92-a7d9-3f3d938302d5" CreationDate="2013-08-05T00:06:19.923" UserId="634" Text="I propose the following guideline: suppose you're teaching a computer science class and a student comes to you with that question. How do you respond?&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In a nutshell, if you just wish the guy would go away, close in situ. If you'd like to help the guy (and the question is about computer science), migrate. In more detail:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; * “What? Is that even English?” → Close (“unclear”).&#xD;&#xA; * “Go read this book.” → Comment, close (too broad).&#xD;&#xA; * “A chimpanzee who'd attended the class would know the answer!” → Close (“unclear”), pray to that the user doesn't come back.&#xD;&#xA; * “What does this have to do with me?” → Close (off-topic).&#xD;&#xA; * “It's a matter of taste.” → Close (opinion-based).&#xD;&#xA; * “That's a direct application of something we covered in class.” → Close (“off-topic, not research-level”), point to a CS.SE reference thread on the topic (e.g. [How to prove that a language is not regular?](http://cs.stackexchange.com/questions/1031/how-to-prove-that-a-language-is-not-regular)).&#xD;&#xA; * “That's a good question about computer science! You see…” → migrate to CS.SE.&#xD;&#xA; * “Ok, here's a hint to solve this exercise, try it and come back.” → migrate to CS.SE.&#xD;&#xA; * “Gee, a programming question.” → migrate to SO if you think it's a really good question, otherwise close as off-topic.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;If none of the categories applies, use your judgement.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;If in doubt — if the question is not great but not crap either — you might as well migrate. If the target site doesn't like the question, it can close it.&#xD;&#xA;" />
PostHistory.xml:4047:  <row Id="5343" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="2714" RevisionGUID="276c9d9f-1a87-4c31-ac55-a44f98c8ab21" CreationDate="2013-08-05T00:11:51.853" UserId="634" Comment="added 571 characters in body" Text="I propose the following guideline: suppose you're teaching a computer science class and a student comes to you with that question. How do you respond?&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In a nutshell, if you just wish the guy would go away, close in situ. If you'd like to help the guy (and the question is about computer science), migrate. In more detail:&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA; * “What? Is that even English?” → Close (“unclear”).&#xD;&#xA; * “Go read this book.” → Comment, close (too broad).&#xD;&#xA; * “A chimpanzee who'd attended the class would know the answer!” → Close (“unclear”), pray to that the user doesn't come back.&#xD;&#xA; * “What does this have to do with me?” → Close (off-topic).&#xD;&#xA; * “It's a matter of taste.” → Close (opinion-based).&#xD;&#xA; * “That's a direct application of something we covered in class.” → Close (“off-topic, not research-level”), point to a Wikipedia page or to a CS.SE reference thread on the topic (e.g. [How to prove that a language is not regular?](http://cs.stackexchange.com/questions/1031/how-to-prove-that-a-language-is-not-regular)).&#xD;&#xA; * “That's a good question about computer science! You see…” → migrate to CS.SE.&#xD;&#xA; * “Ok, here's a hint to solve this exercise, try it and come back.” → migrate to CS.SE.&#xD;&#xA; * “Gee, a programming question.” → migrate to SO if you think it's a really good question, otherwise close as off-topic.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;If none of the categories applies, use your judgement. There is obviously room for subjectivity. Where does [Omega of a polynomial function](http://cs.stackexchange.com/questions/13578/omega-of-a-polynomial-function) fit? I would close and answer with a comment linking to [Wikipedia](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation#Properties), because it's a really elementary question. Also, technically, it isn't a computer science question, it's a math question that falls short of reaching a CS application. I wouldn't say that migrating it is fundamentally wrong, but it is a bit of a waste of effort.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;If in doubt — if the question is not great but not crap either — you might as well migrate. If the target site doesn't like the question, it can close it." />
PostHistory.xml:4071:  <row Id="5368" PostHistoryTypeId="2" PostId="2724" RevisionGUID="6c292f39-534e-4a59-8abb-06ba1196fc7b" CreationDate="2013-09-10T18:17:39.800" UserId="186" Text="There are several reasons to down-vote a post. We have discussed previously that we are not going to require or even demand people to explain their votes. When I see a down-vote that I don't understand I politely comment that I don't understand it, but I think demanding an explanation or stating that there is no reason for the down-vote goes too far. It is not an abuse if people are using their votes in a way different from us.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I have argued a number of times that I am against counter-voting, that is voting to null the effect of other users' vote. Everyone has their own opinion. It is not the job of any particular user to decide what the total should be, the total reflects the opinion of the community. Counter-voting encourages other users to do the same and use their votes to null votes in place of express their opinion about the question. The votes are manifestation of other people's opinions and if we respect other people's opinion then we should respect their votes even when we disagree with them.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In this particular case, I see several possible reasons for a down-vote. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;1. Formating: It is using an image in place of writing it which I think has been one of the reasons people down-vote. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;2. Content: The questions seems to simply ask how to calculate some expression for some particular values. It seems to ask how to apply a method explained in a paper in particular case in practice. It is too localized and it doesn't seem to be a _research-level_ question in _theoretical_ computer science.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I think it is more productive if we comment and explain why we think it is a suitable and interesting question in place of just asking others why they have down-voted the post.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;If you ask me I think we are being too open right now (I guess it is partly because people get bored that there are not as many questions as they would like) to questions which should not be here and are more suitable for CS.SE. E.g. [1](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/18703/are-randomized-algorithms-considered-as-complete), [2](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/18628/confused-about-disparity-and-depth-map), [3](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/18886/proof-that-turing-machine-and-lambda-calculus-are-equivalent), [4](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/18575/pigeon-holing-or-bucketing-a-number-based-on-a-set-of-ranges) have been in closing review queue for sometime but has not been put _on-hold_. Similarly, it is not clear what [this question](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/18871/bounded-computation-and-incompleteness/18883) is asking and should be put _on-hold_ until clarified but it does not have a single close vote. And [this](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/18903/how-would-the-use-of-ternary-computers-change-complexity-of-algorithms) is clearly not-research level in my opinion." />
PostHistory.xml:4072:  <row Id="5369" PostHistoryTypeId="5" PostId="2724" RevisionGUID="9e3ea605-8555-4285-b6f1-0b67dc3e621d" CreationDate="2013-09-10T18:22:49.110" UserId="186" Comment="edited body" Text="There are several reasons to down-vote a post. We have discussed previously that we are not going to require or even demand people to explain their votes. When I see a down-vote that I don't understand I politely comment that I don't understand it, but I think demanding an explanation or stating that there is no reason for the down-vote goes too far. It is not an abuse if people are using their votes in a way different from us.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I have argued a number of times that I am against counter-voting, that is voting to null the effect of other users' vote. Everyone has their own opinion. It is not the job of any particular user to decide what the total should be, the total reflects the opinion of the community. Counter-voting encourages other users to do the same and use their votes to null votes in place of express their opinion about the question. The votes are manifestation of other people's opinions and if we respect other people's opinion then we should respect their votes even when we disagree with them.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;I think it is more productive if we comment and explain why we think it is a suitable and interesting question in place of just asking others why they have down-voted the post.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;In this particular case, I see several possible reasons for a down-vote. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;1. Formating: It is using an image in place of writing the expression which I think has been one of the reasons people down-vote. &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;2. Content: The questions seems to simply ask how to calculate some expression for some particular values. It seems to ask how to apply a method explained in a paper in particular case in practice. It is too localized and it doesn't seem to be a _research-level_ question in _theoretical_ computer science. It is not also unclear what is the trouble the OP is facing in calculating the expression.&#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;If you ask me I think we are being too open right now (I guess it is partly because people get bored that there are not as many questions as they would like) to questions which should not be here and are more suitable for CS.SE. E.g. [1](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/18703/are-randomized-algorithms-considered-as-complete), [2](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/18628/confused-about-disparity-and-depth-map), [3](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/18886/proof-that-turing-machine-and-lambda-calculus-are-equivalent), [4](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/18575/pigeon-holing-or-bucketing-a-number-based-on-a-set-of-ranges) have been in closing review queue for sometime but has not been put _on-hold_. Similarly, it is not clear what [this question](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/18871/bounded-computation-and-incompleteness/18883) is asking and should be put _on-hold_ until clarified but it does not have a single close vote. And [this](http://cstheory.stackexchange.com/questions/18903/how-would-the-use-of-ternary-computers-change-complexity-of-algorithms) is clearly not-research level in my opinion." />
